{"author":"Joe Oakhart","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\n\nThe parent-first claim/transition cascade is thoroughly covered for the sequential,\nsingle-process case (parent-first, multi-level, already-progressed/blocked parent,\nparent-failure-aborts-child, child-failure-after-parent, cycle termination, exit-code\npropagation). There is no test for a cross-process / two-clone race where two agents\nwork different children of the same open parent. The report is right that the expected\nsemantics must be written down before a test can assert them (e.g. may children be\nclaimed independently once the parent is in progress? does a losing parent claim after\nmerge invalidate the corresponding child claim?).\n\n## What\n\nCommitted policy (to be documented, then tested) for two same-parent/different-child\nsub-cases:\n- **(a) Same-tracker, serialized:** agent A claims the parent (cascade) then child A.\n  Agent B, seeing the parent already `in_progress`, does NOT cascade and may claim\n  child B independently under its own assignee. Parent ownership does NOT constrain\n  sibling child assignees. This is fail-fast: if B's parent-claim were attempted while\n  the parent is `open` and lost, B's child is never attempted.\n- **(b) Two offline clones:** both independently claim the (open) parent + a child. On\n  merge, forks are resolved **independently per ticket** by the reducer's UUID tie-break:\n  - The PARENT's STATUS fork resolves to one winner (surfaced as `STATUS_FORK_RESOLVED`\n    on the parent); the losing agent's parent ownership is thereby signaled.\n  - If both clones claimed the SAME child, the CHILD also has a concurrent STATUS fork,\n    resolved by the same tie-break INDEPENDENTLY of the parent — so the child's winner may\n    differ from the parent's winner. If they claimed DIFFERENT children, each child simply\n    carries its own single claim.\n  - In all cases the losing agent's already-written claim (parent and/or child) is **left\n    in place (orphaned under the losing assignee); it is NOT retroactively rolled back or\n    tombstoned.** The signal is `STATUS_FORK_RESOLVED` on the affected ticket(s).\n\nDocument this in `docs/concurrency.md`/`CLAUDE.md`, then encode it in two tests.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `docs/concurrency.md` and/or `CLAUDE.md` (policy statement)\n- `tests/integration/test_concurrency_regression.py` (or sibling) — new race tests\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The ownership policy for BOTH sub-cases above is written down in\n      `docs/concurrency.md`/`CLAUDE.md`, including the explicit rule that a losing parent\n      claim leaves the losing agent's child claim in place (orphaned), detected via the\n      parent's `STATUS_FORK_RESOLVED`.\n- [ ] Same-tracker process race test (sub-case a): two real processes race on one\n      tracker; confirms lock serialization, that B does not cascade a parent already\n      `in_progress`, and both children end claimed under their respective assignees.\n- [ ] Two-clone offline race test (sub-case b): both clones claim parent+child offline,\n      then merge; confirms deterministic convergence, the parent `STATUS_FORK_RESOLVED`\n      signal, that a SAME-child claim produces an independently-resolved child STATUS fork\n      (child winner may differ from parent winner), and that the losing agent's claim(s)\n      remain in place (not rolled back).\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1783890837442748001,"uuid":"a6c7b034-2b33-4665-a23e-80b0f863a6ed"}